7.8\nper cent; three rponths bills, 611.16 per\ncent.\nEast St. Louia Live Stock\nBy AnMci\u00abt\u00abl Press\nEast St. Louis, November 22.\u2014Cattle:\nReceipts, 6,500; steers steady to strong;\nquality common.\nTop\nBulk\nBulk cows\nCanners, bulk\nVeal calves, top.\nBulk\nHpgs: Receipts,\n17,000;\nLG.*'0\n8.00\u00ae 9.W\n5.50@ 7.00\n3.26^: 3.36\n14.76\n14.000.14.a\u00a9\nderporalieed;\nI very little doing after 11 a. m., with sev\neral thousand unsold; general sales 33o\nl.o 50c below\u2019 Saturday\u2019s average.\nEarly top 11.26\nLate top U.W\nBulk .%.10.00@11.23\nSheep: Receipts, 2^000; slow; 26c to 60c\nlower on lambs and sheep; choice heavy\nfed western lambs averaging 8J) pounds\n$10.76.\nChoice natives, 82-pound aver\nage U.W\nBulk 3.50@10.*,5\nEwes, top 4-50\nBulk 4.00@ 1.50\nChicago Live Stock\nBy AftNoclaied Pres\u00ab\nChicago, November 22.\u2014Cattle: Re\nceipts, 31,1)00; good and choice corn-fed\nsteers scarce and 25c to 50c lower; top,\nM6.75; steers below 1,100 mostly steady,\nbut slow. t>f\nBulk natives 8.75@1J.0U\nBulk westerns 7.00\u00ae8.30\nGood butcher cows. 4.50\u00ae 8.75\nBulk canners 3.26\u00ae 3.00\nVeal calves, bulk. 14.00@14 50\nHogs: Receipts, 62,000; opened 50c to \u00bb)0c\nlower; late mostly 75c lower, closing\nfairly active at 75c to fl lower.\nTop early U.4U\nPractical top late U.oo\nBulk 10.6G@ll.t5\nBulk desirable 100 to 130-pound\npigs U.00@U.t3\nSheep: Receipts, 41,000; fat lambs 50c to\n75c lower.\nTop fed westerns early.$ U\nBulk natives .10.00@U.W\nChoice aged wethers.\nTop feeder lambs early. 1201\nCoffee Market\nBy Associated Pre\u00bbs\nNew York, November 22.\u2014There was\nsome further switching in the market\nfor coffee futures today, but business\n?ener&l}y was very quiet and the price\nmovement narrow\u2019. First prices were\nto J* points lower in resrxmse to weak\nness in Rio Exchange rates and reports\nnf lower milreis prices, but later cables\nshowed a rally in Santos futures, and\nLhc market here steadied a few points\nfrom the lowest. March contracts ad\nvanced from 7.0\u00a9c to 7.16c and closed a^\ni.ilc with the general market showing a\nnet decline of 4 to 8 points. December.\ni.3Sc; January. 6.\u00ab2c; March, 7.Uc; May,\n.51c; July. 7.83c: September, 8.08c.\nSpot coffee quiet; Rio 7s. 7c; Santos\nIs, lO&HAfrc. Cost and freight offer* in\ncluded Santos 4s at l-6e; Kio 7s at\n\u00bb.50c, American credits. The early cable\nshowed an advance of 10\u00a9 reis in the\niollar buying rate and a decline of S-16d\nn Rio exchange on London. Rio futures\nwere 100 to 160 reis lower and Santos un\nchanged to 10 reis lower, but later Santo*\nwas quoted unchanged to 1\u00ae reis higher.\nBrasilian port receipts, 54,000; Jundlahy\n\u2022ecetpts, 38,000; Santos cleared 48,3*0 for\nNew York.\nBy\nNew York,\n7 7-16c.\nSpot Coffee\nAseoeOated\nNovember 32.\u2014Spot coffee.\nSent Market\nBr Associated grass\nNew York, November 22.\u2014The an\nnouncement that the president of Cuba\nmay declare an embargo on sugar had\nlittle influence In the local, raw .sugar\nmarket today and prices were un\nchanged at 4%e for Cuban, cost and\nfreight, equal to 15.76 for Centrifugals.\nThere were aalea of 5.200 bags of Luban\nreported.\nThe market for refined was quiet and\nunchanged at 59 to 56.50 for fine gran\nulated. In sugar futures some un\neasiness was expreseed that the em\nbargo may result in some delay in the\nsugar to be apqfiod on contract and\nthere vak a scattered oovering move\nment in evidence with closing prices\n20 to 30 points net higher.\nMotel Market\nNew York, November 22.\u2014Copper, nom\nInal; electrolytic spot and nearby,\n1\u00ab406454: first quarter, 1454015.\nIron quiet. No.. 1 northern. 545040; No.\n2 northern. 04046; No. 2 southern 538040.\nTin easy, spot and nearby 535.05006.50;\nfutures, 537037.25; antimony. 0; lead,\neasier, spot, 16 7500.50; zinc quiet. East\nSt. Louis delivery, spot #*00.1234.\nLondon, November 22.\u2014Standard cop\nper \u00a38 12a \u00abd: futures fflls 6d; electrolytic,\nspot, ,\u00a390; futures, \u00a382. Tin, spot 1221\n5s. Futures. 1234 So. Lead, spot \u00a330 15s;\nfutures \u00a32* 15s. Zinc, spot \u00a384 Its; fu\nture. 04 17s Cd.\nCattea Sod Oil\nNew York. November 22.\u2014Cotton\nseed oil dropped another quarter jont\ntoday in line with other commodity\nmarkets, but a more friendly feelinr\nDaily FinartcijlI Gossip\nBy HOLLAND\nNew York, November 22.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nWhen any one who has had dealings in\nsecurities received from his broker a re\nquest to a command that the margin car\nrying the stocks be increased, then the\nquestion has arisen whether he shall\nmeet this demand or let the broker sell\nthe securities. Sometimes operators have\nfound that their brokers were demanding\nas much as 30 per cent margin. Many\ntimes the brokers insisted that margins\nbe increased so that it has often hap\npened in this tim6 of falling market for\nsecurities that the operator has let them\ngo. He has found that he cannot afford\nto pay the increased rate for the use of\nmoney which has been a characteristic of\nthe call money market for some time.\nCareful investigation justifies the opin\nion that one of the reasons and perhaps\nthe chief reason for the depreciation in\nthe securities market is to be found in\nthe demahd for larger and larger mar\ngins. For a few days this demand has\ndecreased and the fact that it ha^ done\nso is accepted as one of several reasons\nfor hoping that depressing conditions in\nthe securities market or further liquida\ntion have about ended. In fact, it is\nobserved that many of those who are\nfamiliar with conditions not only of the\npresent time, bift of the past, feel justi\nfied in\u2019 saying that one of these days a\nchange will come which will bo con\ntinued until the securities market ma>\nbe of such activity as to justify speak\ning of it as one of the greatest bull mar\nkets this country has ever known. Those\nwho forecast the coming of a great mar\nket of this kind base their opinion upon\nsome of the present day conditions to\nwhich the bankers referred in (heir re\ncent metings at the office of J. Mor\ngan Co. The men who met in Mr.\nMorgan's officer as a whole, stand pre\neminent among the bankers and finan\nciers of New York. The association of\nall of them are not merely local, but\nnation-wide and in some cases interna\ntional. Wlthoout exception these bankers\nare reported to have agreed that the\nbanking situation throughout the entire\ncountry is one which is worthy of grati\nfication. This condition was put laconi\ncally by one of the bankers, who said\nthat there are no sore spots in the situa\ntion,, bic or little.\nWHEN WILL IT COME\nBut. the expected great and possibly\nphenomenal activity in the securities\nmarket will not come until several mat\nters have been satisfactorily disposed of.\nThese chiefly refer to deflation and this\ndeflation, President Sabin of the Guar\nanty Trust company says, must continue\nuntil there is complete liquidation of\ncommodities, securities and labor. Already\nit is underway in the manufacturing in\ndustries. It is not so much in evi\ndence in retail transactions although all\nagree that the retailers must yield to\nthis influence sooner or laterr- If they\ndo not, then they will be confronted\nwith the fact that the public continues\nto refrain from buying anything'but the\nnecessaries of life and as little of them\nas possible\nWHY OUTLOOK IS GRATIFYING\nAlthough this is a peri<#] of conva.es\ncence from feverish conditions occasioned\nby war, nevertheless many are the rea\nLOCAL SECURITIES\nBank Stocks\nBid. Asked.\nAmerican Tr. Sava. Bank 145 f6b\njB'ham Trust Sc Savs. Co. 285 305\nFirst National Bank 306 326\nTraders National Bank 145 ltw\nInsurance Stock\u2014$10 Par\nInterstate Casualty Co.\n03 2-3 par) 3\n[Great Southern Life Ins. Co. 32 lb\nj Southern States Fire Ins. Co. 3% 2\ni Protective Life Ins. Co.... 34 20\nLand and Building Co. Stocks\nBirmingham Keaity Co. 135 150\nCham, of Com., pfd. (par 125) 5 10\nElmwood Cemetery Corp.... SO HO\nEnsley Land Co. 90 106\nFairfield Land Co. 65 80\nIndustrial and Miscellaneous Stocks\nAmerican Bakeries Co. 105 12b\nAvondale Mills, common. 500 660\nAvondale Mills, pfd.. 101 110\nBessemer C. I. L. Co... 60 70\nB ham Macaroni Co. 310 125\nJeflerson County Bank. IS 36\nL., J. L., common 50 60\nU, J. L., pfd.65 85\nMorris Plan So 100\nNational C. I. P. Co. 140 1 to\ni Realty Tr. Co.. Class B, pfd 110 130\nRealty Tr. Co., Class D, pfd. 301 106\nRealty Tr. Co., common. 100 226\nMunicipal Bond}*\nState of Alabama, 3Vfes (i956) 77 81\nState of Alabama, 4s (1956) 86 90\nJeff. County 4.00 to CVi per\ncent basis.\nJeff. County 8 pet. Warrants. .101 104\nCity of B\u2019ham, 6. per cent basis.\nMiscellaneous Bonds\nAla. Power Co. notes.. 6 1922 96 97\nAla. Power Co. 5 1946 77 80\nAla. State Fair 6 1926 30 46\nI Ala. Trac. L. P.... 5 1962 41 44\nAla. Water Co. 6 1932 90 100\nAla. Water Co. notes.. 6 1922 90 96\nAla. S. S. Bldg. Co. 6 1930 97 190\nB\u2019ham Ry. Elec. Co. 5 1 924 96 loo\nB\u2019liam Ry., L P... 4Vi 1951 62 68\nB\u2019ham Ry.. L F.... 6 1967 61 67\nB\u2019ham Water Works Co. 6 1921 97 100\nB\u2019ham Water Works Co. 5 1SB6 75 80\nCountry Club S 1933 90 100\nJeff. R. Bldg. 8 1938 100 110\nMilner Land Co. 7 1924 90 96\nMilner Land Co. 1st\nmortgage 6 1923 100 lflb\nMonteva.!lo Mining Co. 6 1928 92 96\nPratt Con. Coal Co. 5 1955 65 75\nWoodward Iron Co. 5 1952 74 77\nprevailed near the close and a ally\ntook place on short covering and local\nbuying for a reaction. Spot^ trade\nshowed no improvement and crude\nmarkets were lower. Final bids were\nfive points lower to eight let higner.\nSales, 14,100 barrels; tenders, $5;\nprime crude. $6. Sales, prime summer\nyellow* spot closed at $8.50; Oeco.-noer,\n$8.75; March. $9.27; May, $9.48. all Lid.\nNarml Stores\nBy Associated Press\nSavannah, Ga., November 22.\u2014Turpen\ntine steady, 92c. Sales, none; receipts,\n321; shipments, 106; stock, 16,880. Rosin\nquiet. Sales, none; receipts, 772; ship\nments, 2,072; stock, 63,610.\nQuote: B. D, E, F, G, H, I, K, M, N,\nV^G, WW, $11.\nLondon has long had the reputation\nof being a great shipping point, al\u00ab\nthough the shipping has been done at\nTilbury, which is 26 miles down thi\nriver from London. Recently enormoul\nconcrete docks have been completed in\nthe verjr heart of London and the city\nnow is a port.\nWhen the Brooklyn bridge was com\npleted over the East River, 37 years\nago, many people doubted its stability\nand predicted its collapse. It is car\nrying many times the original load of\ntraffic and has shown no signs of\nweakness.\nJapanese\nGovernment\n4\u00a3s Due 1925\nYield About 11 Per Cent\nDetails on Rcqaest.\nWard, Sterne\nCompany\nSloe In I\u2014da llortya g\u2014\n304-308 Brown-Marx Building\nMein 595\u20144390\nsons for believing that various influ\nences are slowly but surely aq^ing in\nco-operation so that, in clue time, it may\nbe three months or six months, condi\ntions will be normal. This view is not\na local one exclusively. It is shared by\nGeorge M. Reynolds and by the Forgan\nBrothers of Chicago, and by some of the\nnfluential men of Boston and other\ncities.\nIt is proclaimed by bankers, who arc\nmen of influence in Cleveland, that the\nspontaneous economics now practiced\nby the American people have put an end\nto extravagance. They speak of the in\ncrease in the efficiency of labor. This is\nespecially noticeably in some of the in\ndustries of the mid-west. The purchas\ning power of thfc dollar is rising. There\nseems to be no doubt that easier money\nwill be in sight. And the opinion com\nmonly held by business men in Ohio is\nthat the present lull in business will be\nat an end by early spring.\nMEXICO AN1) PROSPERITY\nThe outlook for an early establishment\nof cordial relation between Mexico and\nfhe United States is so good that this in\nternational situation is sure to stimu\nlate to some extent at least our own\nprosperity. Other factors which are\nworking hand in hand for the return of\nprosperity are first of all the unprece\ndented crops which were cultivated last\nsummer and harvested in the fall\nNext. but of equal importance, is til\nrecognized improvement in the railroad\ncondition. This improvement has been\nmore rapid than was expected when it\nbegan in the summer. The i>eak of the\ndemand for credit 'has been reached, and\nit was probably to this that, Jleroert Hoo\nver referred when he said recently, that,\nmaintaining our foreign trade are secured\nthere is no doubt of the return of pros\nper ty for all other conditions favor\nsuch Return. The federal reserve bank\nbig system has justified its existence. It\nhas made it possible to withstand\nred it strain which*- was not only the\ngreatest in our history, but of which\nnone of those who aided in the legislation\nupon which this system Is based had at\nthe time the slightest comprehension.\nWe are to have continued enormous for\neign demand for almost all of our prod\nucts, and especially manufactures i.nd\nthe agencies are now under way where\nby this demand can be satisfactorily\nI lincanced. Furthermore every one who\n's familiar with the' values of various\nsecurities reports that the market quo\ntations for the majority of the securi\nties at this time represent values which\nare far below' the inherent value which\nare in these properties. By and by when\nthe bull market comes these inherent\nvalues will be recognized and will in\nfluence quotations. All sa\\. however,\nthat this is a poor time to speculate,\nhut some are of the opinion that if any\nhas a't hand a considerable amount of\nmoney or even a few thousand dollars\nhe would not go far astray if he were\nto buy outright certain securities and\nthen lock them in his safe deposit box.\nwaiting in confidence for the time when\nkey w\u2019ill appreciate, although bearing in\nmind the fact that the government will,\nunless excess profits tax is eliminated,\nreach forth and take a considerable part\nof these profits.\nGENERAL BUYING OF WHEAT\nCOLLAPSED, CAUSING BIG\nDROP IN COUNTRY\u2019S STAPLE\nliy Associated Press\nChicago, November 22.\u2014Paralysis of\nthe general buying Jed to a collapse\nof ll%c a bushel today in the price\nof wheat. The market afterward ral\nlied a little, but th^ close was semi\ndemoralized 2% to 9c net lower, with\nDecember $1.60 to 1.60% and March\n'$1.55 to 1.56. Corn gained to 2%c\nand oats lost to 1 In provisions,\nthere was a set-back ranging from 57c\nto $1.50.\nAlmost complete lack of confidence\nin the bull side of the wheat market\nwas shown by a majority of traders.\nSome of the more adventurous spirits\nin the pit evinced a disposition at the\nI outset to act 911 opinions that a de\ncided reaction was due after the dras\n1 tic liquidation which of late had been\nforced on speculative holders. In\ncreased selling pressure that quickly\n\u25a0developed in, however, made would-be\nj purchasers take fright, and appeared\nto center attention more than ever on\nI bearish aspects of the situation. Down\nward swings of wheat prices there\nupon increased in violence, despite\nword of export business totaling 1.000.\n000 bushels and notwithstanding a big\ndecrease in the visible supply total.\nThe sole important exception was that\nshorts in March delivery covered ac\ntively at the last.\nCorn and oats* in sympathy with\nthe weakness of wheat, dragged celow\nany records since 1015. but then corn\n(became firmer. It was said that a\n(leading bear speculator in corn was\nreducing his commitments.\nAcute depression in the hog market\nsent provisions down grade.\nChicago Futures\nBy Associated Pres*\nChicago. November 22.--Future qu\ntatioiis were as follows\nWheat\u2014 Open. Tlierh\nDec.\nMar.\nCorn\u2014\nMay\nOats\u2014\nDec.\nMay\nPork\u2014\nJan.\nLard\u2014\nJan.\nMay _\nRibs\u2014\n1.60\n1.60 V,\n.65%\n.70%\n.4 1\nIS\n1.70\n1.62\n.65%\n.71%\n.4 1\n.40%\nL57%\n1.52%\n.01%\n.68%\