 nervousness\nand^irregularity today but a break which\nI carried December and some of the later\nI months into new low ground for the\nseason was followed by sharp rallies, the\nmarket closing very steady, 5 to 51 points\nI Tiet higher. January contracts broke\nfrom lt>.25c to 15.13c, and closed at 16.19c.\nI The market opened steady at a decline\nI of 22 points to an advance of 22 points,\nnear months being influenced by Decem\nber liquidation and weak cables, while\nlater deliveries were higher on covering.\n1 \u25baecember sold up to 16.50e and March\nto 16.20c*. right after the call, with ac\ntive months generally showing net ad\nvances of if. to :)7 points, but the demand\nwas readily supplied and prices soon\nturned easier again. Liquidation of De\ncember continued, while there was south\nern selling of the later months with a\nrenewal of local and Wall street pres\nsure encouraged by full ginning returns,\nbearish spot advices and reports that cot\nton shipped on consignment to Kurope\nwas was not selling freely. The market\nwas very weak and unsettled during the\nmiddle of the day in consequence, with\nDecember selling off to 15.65c and March\nto 14.90c. This attracted more active\ncovering and the market was firmer late\nin the day on reports of a better tone in\nthe stock market and of an improved\ndemand for spot cotton in Savannah.\nLast prices showed rallies of GO to\npoints of the lowest. There were ru\nmors during the day that middling cotton\nwas offering as low as 13c at some in\nterior points in the Carolinas and that\nstrict middling had sold at 14c and 14Vjc\nin Charlotte, N. C., territory on Satur\nday.\nPort receipts 30.731: V. S. port stocks,\n1,327,690.\nNew* York Futures\nn v \\NAOchiteri Pres*\nNew York, November 22. \u2014The cotton\nmarket closed very steady.\nHigh. Low. Close\nDecember 16.50 15.55 1630\nJanuary 16 25 jf.-15 16.17\nMarch .t 16.20 15.35 16.05\ny. a .16.16 15.30 15.93\nJuly 15.9S 15.15 15.75\nNew Orleans CoWon\n\u00abv Associated Press\nNew Orleans. November 22.\u2014During- a\ngood part of the session today the price\nof rot ton \\va: depressed by the heavy\nginning to November 14, but in tho\nj late trading the market was very steady\non realizing purchases by shorts anct\nnew buying for long account, based on\nreports of easier money conditions in\nthe south and 5 per cent call money in\nNew York. One report had it that in\nsome interior markets factors were so\nliciting consignments of cotton and ad\nvertising that they would lend money\non lots that were to bo stored.\nThe census bureau figures of 8,920,770\nbales ginned to November 14 were alto\ngether higher than expected and they\ncaused recessions of 4 to 2b points\naround the opening, but the market re\nacted almost immediately under realis\ning by shorts and rose as high as levels\n26 to 42 points over the close of Satur\nday. When it was pointed out that the\nginning report meant that the output\nthis last period was 1,449,000 bales, against\n1.299,000 the same period last year 929,\n000,000 two years ago, selling commenced\nI again, and this time prices were forced\n29 to 57 points under the final prices of\nSaturday, some months making new low\nlevels for tho season. December fell to\n1*14.84c, which compared with 15.80c as the\nhigh of the day.\nThe market was very steady in the last,\nhour of the session and the close was\nio 31 points net higher on the day.\nNew\nNew Orleans futures\nBy A\u00ab<on\u00bbitfl Tret*\nOrleans, November 22.\u2014The\nLow. Close.\n14.84 15.45\nton market closed steady at net ad\nvances of 5 to 31 points.\nHigh\nDecember 15.80\n.January 15.68\nMarch 1 5.61\nMay 15.45\nJuly 15.27\n14.70\n14.71\n1 4.60\n14.55\n15.38\n15.40\n15.2S\n15.15\nSpot Cotton\nBy Associated Press\nNew Orleans, November 22.\u2014Spot cot\nton quiet; 25 lower. Sales on the spot,\n163 bales; to arrive, 1,250. Low middling,\n11c; middling, 16e; good middling, 18.25c.\nReceipts, 9.579; stock, 376,766.\nNew York, November 22